Shout out to Hans Christian Andersen! The creative storybook genius is forever memorialized in Copenhagen with The Little Mermaid statue. When we approached the bustling crowd fighting to take pictures and get as close to the statue as possible, we were a bit surprised. The little mermaid was actually quite petite. After our initial thoughts of being underwhelmed, we realized, there is thought behind the size of the statue. We thought it spoke to the delicate nature of us as human beings and our personal desires to find happiness by any means necessary. Not to mention the backdrop is gorgeous!
.
.
.
.
Travel Tip: Tour groups usually get to the statue in the late mornings. To avoid the crowds and get a little one on one time with the mermaid try to get there pretty early. It is also very nice to have a backdrop that doesn’t have a tourist cruise going on!
.
.
.

We cannot wait to be back in this beautiful city in a couple weeks!! Barcelona has one of the most eclectic architectural experiences that I have ever seen. You can go from seeing traditional Spanish style buildings, to medieval gothic structures, to entire parts of the city created by artist Antoni Gaudí. Just walking around this city is like a fairy tale. One of our favorite things to do is grab a couple Estrella beers, a cone of iberico ham, and just stroll around looking at the sights. Talking about a relaxing time!
.
.
.
.
What city is your favorite architectural experience?
.
.
.
.
Travel Tip: Be a local and go to the markets and outdoor sights early. There is nothing worse than going to a market shoulder to shoulder with people while you are trying to admire the beauty of catalan food or try to take a picture with the buildings and the next thing you know you have an unexpected friend in your photo. .
.
.

Thailand is the place we keep saying we want to go back. The complete change in our normal day to day allowed us to appreciate how large the world is. We loved the delicious day markets, the crazy night markets, and the beauty of the temples. There are over forty-thousand temples just in Thailand. Each one of them makes you think of how much time and thought went into each design and brush stroke. Every piece from the color to the different animals depicted in the structures tells a story. Here you see the many spires of Wat Phra Kaew at the Grabd Palace. .
.
.
What area of the world do you have an intense desire to return to?
.
.
.
.
Travel Tip: If you want to save some money (and have a relatively strong stomach) eat and drink mostly at the street markets. This is an amazing cultural experience, and keeps you away from the overpriced restaurants that cater to tourists. .
.
.

London has many iconic bridges. There’s the Millennium Bridge, London Bridge, Westminster Bridge, but our favorite by far is Tower Bridge! This was my first time in London and Jim’s millionth time, so we did an all city tour. The unfortunate thing about this tour by Jim was that it was completely walking...it was also January. As I froze my tail off in between locations, I thanked London’s generosity of having a warm pub at every corner to defrost my fingers with a nice pint! .
.
.
.
What are your favorite London attractions?
.
.
.
.
Travel Tip: One of our favorite places to eat is right near Tower Bridge called Borough Market. Here you can sample many different local fare including local cheeses, meats, and seafood. It’s a great way to get a great view of the diverse food culture London has to offer. .
.

Florence was one of our favorite cities we had the chance to visit in Italy. It is an incredibly walkable city with amazing food around every corner. One of our favorite parts of Florence was the historical significance and the story behind different pieces of architecture. The Duomo is one of the biggest tourist attractions in Florence, and with this picture you can probably understand why. It’s beautiful! This city is filled with sneaky pieces of art and architecture that have amazing stories behind them. One of our favorites, Perseus with the head of Medusa, was at the Piazza della Signoria which houses many amazing statues depicting various parts of Greek and Roman history. .
.
.
.
Travel Tip: There are many local guides at reasonable prices around Florence that will show you more than the average tour guide. Even some of the statues on random buildings tell a story. Make sure you don’t miss out!
.
.

Akihabara in Tokyo is an interesting sight. The anime and video game capital of the world introduced us to scantily clad anime figures, video game lounges, and high pitched women dressed in skimpy costumes trying to get us to their themed restaurant. It was a fun experience as everywhere you look there is something shiny to look at. The bright lights entice you to investigate even the most boring sounding activity even more. Somehow Jim and I stumbled upon a pool hall, and we never play pool. It is also an area where many go to escape reality. Whether you like being waited on by a maid as you dine on cute looking deserts or just want to see the next greatest VR world, this part of Tokyo has it.
.
.
.
.
Akihabara reminds us that there are many ways to destress and escape the every day grind. What do you do to take a break from your normal routine?
.
.
.
.
Travel Tip: Tokyo is a large city with many different cities inside of it. Each of them presenting a different delightful vibe. We found the JR Pass made traveling from the different areas of the city much easier. You will have to apply for the JR Pass before you arrive in Japan. If you are looking to go outside the city to maybe Kyoto or Osaka, the JR Pass is much more cost friendly than buying individual train tickets. .

So we found a couple new friends! During our safari in Kruger we stumbled across a large herd of elephants. We came to learn that elephants are like the parents of the wild. During times of drought elephants will actually knock down trees so the smaller animals can eat and survive. This made us reflect on what we can do for less fortunate individuals out there and encourage us to be a greater part of our world community. Needless to say, elephants are now our favorite animal. Not just for their beauty, but their brain as well! .
.
.
.
How do you participate to help the global community? Looking for some ideas for us to participate in. .
.
.
.
Travel tip: When booking your safari make sure you ask them a couple questions before you book. Is the Jeep open air? Is there a tracker on the Jeep? And most importantly, is the jeep allowed to go off-road? These three questions can completely change your safari experience. Some places do not offer this and you can only see the animals from a distance. .
.
.
.

Notre Dame exceeded our expectations. This photo does not do the sheer mass and intricacies justice. Linh and I got lucky as we entered the cathedral a Sunday service was about to begin. Not to completely bring religion into this, but to say attending a mass in one of the most iconic cathedral in the world is a life changing is an understatement. Regardless of where your religion lies, it reminds us that we all have our beliefs and values that guide us through life. Fortunately for us, it has brought us to experience many cultures that completely evolve our way of thinking. .
.
.
.
What has been your favorite cultural experience that has evolved your views of the world?
.
.
.
.
Travel Tip: On the first Sunday’s of the month during the off season entry to Notre Dame, as well as many other museums, are free to enter. Even though this is one of the less expensive historical experiences, we are trying to save you money where we can. This opens up some cash for a pint or champagne! 🍾🍻 .
.

We see many photos OF the Eiffel Tower, but how many do we see FROM the Eiffel Tower? We believe both uncover beauty. From this vantage point it is easy to see why Paris’ nickname is the Cory of love. Every portion of the city stirs up emotion. We look at a different areas of the city and think about what it would be like if our lives were different. Playing football next to the Seine River, spending our days cruising up and down the river, or having a nice picnic with a fresh baguette and bottle of wine. Everywhere we go we try to take a step back and think what it would be like and appreciate all that we have.
.
.
.
What is your favorite part of Paris? Share with us!
.
.
.
Travel Tip: There are many local guides that offer affordably priced tours in Paris. They offer a wide variety of options from history focused to culinary focus, they have everything!
.
.

If you can’t tell already, we love a good sunset! This picture was taken as we ended our trip to Italy. It is the perfect reflection of our trip coming to an end. The sun sets on another day ending, but not before it shows us one last show, a reminder of its beauty. From Roman Colosseum, to the colored buildings of Positano, to the culinary delights that were cooked with love, Italy really does have it all. .
.
.
A trip coming to an end is a surreal moment. Do you do anything special to remember your travels? This might be a bit weird, but we like to collect a piece of dirt or sand from each place we visit. .
.
.
.
Travel Tip: There are many street vendors in Florence, many of them selling leather goods. If you are in the market for a purse, backpack, or jacket, this is the place. Make sure you haggle with the merchants as you can manage some really great finds!
.
.
.

This city is like a painting! For my birthday Linh surprised me with a island hopping trip off of Positano. As we departed the Positano harbor, the city’s true colors began to shine. We had a rare expansive view of the many different house colors perched upon the hill. It reminds us that no matter how different we all might be, there is beauty in all of us! Sometimes we just need to remind ourselves of it!
.
.
.
How do you empower yourself? One activity I use is positive affirmations. Every day I have a positive phrase that I say while looking into the mirror and repeat it until I feel it. It’s a great way to start the day and has changed the way I approach the world!
.
.
.
Travel Tip: If you are trying to do island hopping off of Amalfi Coast, make sure you do your research. While we were hopping from island to island and grotto to grotto, we saw many tourist boats packed like sardines. Before you book go towards the water and try to haggle to get a more private experience. It will be worth it!
.
.
.
.

Yes, we did the tourist thing. Pont des Arts, also know as love lock bridge, is a beautiful sight to see as you get to be right in the middle of the Seine River with fantastic 360 view of the city. You can even make out Norte Dame in the small island in the background. The tale is that placing your names on a lock and throwing the key in the Seine River is a sign of committed love. Linh and I have taken this to heart and our love continues to grow every day. .
.
.
Do you and your significant other have a special representation of committed love? Share with us!
.
.
.
Travel Tip: Get lost! One of our favorite experiences in this city was to just walk in a certain direction and take in all the sights. The great thing is if you stumble upon a beautiful building or historic sign, there are many apps that provide an augmented reality description of what you are looking at. That means a free tour, on your time! Ask us for which apps we use for travel. .
.

The lights going down in the eternal city. This was our first time in Rome and it completely exceeded our high expectations. You can tell the citizens of Rome put the utmost detail and class in everything they do. From the food to the amazing architecture, Rome does it right! The stillness of the water under the bridge gives us a sense of calm and tells us no matter how rocky the waters of our future get, there is always a bridge to lend a helping hand. The waters will calm again. .
.
.
Sunsets are one of our favorite images to capture as it represents a city shedding its light and showing a new side of itself. Where are your favorite sunsets?
.
.
.
.
Travel Tip: make sure you have your head on a swivel in Rome. Almost every building seems to have been methodically thought out to achieve maximum beauty. Do not forget to live in the moment!
.

This city is like walking through a painting! Taking a stroll through the cobblestone streets transports you to a time when famed author Hans Christian Andersen was at his peak. It is no wonder how this city inspired this man to create such stories as The Little Mermaid, The Ugly Ducking, and Thumbelina. Linh and I were fortunate to start our our fairytale here. Except ours revolves around the culinary delights this city has to offer. .
.
.
What city have you visitors that evoked you starting your own personal fairytale?
.
.
.
Travel Tip: The canal water is incredibly clean. There are many outdoor public pools that are fed by the canals. I ventured out there early one morning and it was one of the most refreshing swims of my life. Highly recommended!
.

Versailles, an epic experience. The palace itself encrusted in gold shimmers in even the darkest of days. As much as we enjoyed the palace tour. The pièce de résistance for us was the gardens. The gardens house over 400 sculptures/fountains, each of them telling a beautiful story. As we strolled through the gardens, Linh and I were just thinking about all of the creative minds that put their mark on this campus of beauty. It is truly a remarkable sight to see. .
.
.
What has been your favorite garden that you have experienced and what was your pièce de résistance? Tag us in your thoughts! .
.
.
Travel Tip: When we booked our tour for Versailles we mixed it with another tour. We had about 3 hours at the palace and gardens and feel we barely scratched the surface. If you are planning to go to Versailles, make sure you allocate a whole day to take your time and really be in the moment. .
.

Whenever we travel we always make it a goal to get away from the traditional “tourist” areas to really embark on an adventure. On our beautiful beach hugging drive to Sintra we stumbled upon this little city on a cliff. In that moment we transported ourselves to what it would be like to live there. Walking down the cobblestones to the local markets, go swimming in the public pool (you can see it in the middle of the photo), and waking up every morning with the ocean breeze running through our hair as we peer into the vast ocean. Paradise?
.
.
.
What is your ideal paradise? For us it would be living in a historical foodie city on the water...with close proximity to an international airport! 😂
.
.
.
.
Travel Tip: In Lisbon there are many small local places to eat and drink in Bairro Alto area. This was our favorite place to visit as you got to experience the tight historical streets lined with bars and restaurants. This is a great way to sample many different types of local fare at a reasonable price. .
.

This image of Linh looking over the South African savanna represents Linh and my dreams meshing into reality. Since we met, we have always had a lust for travel, experiencing other cultures, and trying every food on this great planet. As time progresses we feel lucky that we are working toward our dreams every day. .
.
.

.
.
.

.
.
.
Every once in a while when life seems to challenge me, I take a step back, take a breath, and reflect on the countless blessings. What type of reflection do you do in difficult times?
.
.
.

.
.

.
.
.
Travel tip: When visiting Cape Town make sure you get out of the city. Some of the most beautiful sights are a quick 20-30 minute drive outside of city center. .

Sun setting over one of my favorite cities. The energy and culture of London fills you with tradition and love. View from the top of St. Paul’s Cathedral. .
.
If you could live in one city that you have traveled to where would it be? For me, it’s London. It is a gateway to many other cities, the food culture is incredible, and it puts me closer to my #chelseafc .
.
.
Travel Tip: London can be an expensive city. The public transportation system is incredibly efficient and easy to navigate. Save some coin by avoiding taxis and traffic and grab an Oyster card. .
